		<header>
			
			<h1>New MRLs could heavily affect pear and apple sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 March 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The EC has decided to significantly reduce maximum residue levels (MRLs) for a pesticide that is used to avert “superficial scalding” of deciduous fruit held in cold storage. The diphenylamine (DPA) MRL was reduced from 5 mg/kg in apples and 10 mg/kg in pears to 0.1 mg/kg as a transitional measure from 2 February 2014, and from July 2015, “DPA residues will no longer be allowed.”</p><p>It has been estimated that in the absence of alternative permitted treatments, the new EU MRL regulations on DPA “could affect 3.5 million tonnes of pears and apples in Europe”, with economic losses in excess of €1,000 million per annum. This could see production of many varieties dropping “to levels that the market can absorb in a short period of time as they would be untreated”. &nbsp;</p><p>Research is under way into “alternative methods of controlling superficial scald”.</p><p>Meanwhile, according to analysis published by USDA, the South African deciduous fruit industry has been helped by the weakening rand which “has bolstered exports to Europe, Russia, the Middle East, and African markets”, despite rising shipping costs.</p><p>Traditionally, the UK and Germany have been the primary markets for South African deciduous fruit exports, but concerns over future developments in the EU market are forcing the South African deciduous fruit industry to “focus greater attention on Middle Eastern and Asian markets”.&nbsp; Markets in Africa for apples are also being developed: exports to Benin and Angola have increased by 72% since 2010, and these markets have risen as a proportion of total exports from 9.8 to 13.2%.</p><p><b>South African fresh apple exports (tonnes)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
