				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Given the time required in cold store for apples and pears traded between Southern Africa and the EU, the new MRL regulation could fall particularly heavily on nations that export deciduous fruit.</p><p>In recent years South Africa has been developing deciduous fruit exports to a range of non-traditional markets, with strong annual growth (albeit from a very low base), but the EU remains the major market. Any diversion of exports to alternative markets would be likely to carry significant revenue implications.</p><p>With research into alternative methods of controlling superficial scalding already taking place, the scope for deferring the date for the introduction of the prohibition on DPA residues could usefully be explored. Similar deferments were granted during the EU’s major pesticides review when alternative treatments were not at that time available.</p>
		</div>
		
